{"questionId":"28010","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>The position vector of a particle at time <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math> is given by <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">i</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mo>(</mo><mn>3</mn><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">j</mi></math>.&nbsp;Displacement is measured in metres and time is measured in seconds.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>Hence show that the acceleration is always directed towards the origin.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo> </mo><mi>cos</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">i</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mi>sin</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">j</mi></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>M1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">r</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;(where <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">r</mi></math> is a position vector from the origin)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">a</mi></math> is in opposite direction to the position vector&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>R1</strong></em></p>\n<p>hence&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"bold-italic\">a</mi></math> is always directed towards the origin&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;<em><strong>AG</strong></em></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[3 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"28010","referenceCode":"22N.2.AHL.TZ0.7b.ii","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"Hence show that the acceleration is always directed towards the origin.","paper":"2","level":"HL","questionNumber":"b.ii","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 3]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 5—Calculus","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.9—Differentiating standard functions and derivative rules","Topic 5—Calculus","AHL 5.13—Kinematic problems","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.10—Vector definitions","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","AHL 3.12—Vector applications to kinematics"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}